Practical Lab - 3

Univariate Linear Regression¶

The report is to analyze the relationship between median house value (dependent value) and different independent values from the California housing Prices Dataset using a linear regression model. The report includes exploratory data analysis, visualization of the data distribution. The linear regression model is trained, evaluated on both training and test sets, and performance metrics such as Mean Squared Error and Mean Absolute Error are reported to assess the model's predictive capabilities.

Getting the Data¶

Data Sourcecode link - Kaggle_california_housingprices_dataset

Linear Regression¶

Define and Train the model

In [7]:
# fit between median_income and median_house_value
model1 = LinearRegression().fit(housing[['median_income']], housing['median_house_value'])

# fit between population and median_house_value
model2 = LinearRegression().fit(housing[['population']], housing['median_house_value'])

# fit between households and median_house_value
model3 = LinearRegression().fit(housing[['households']], housing['median_house_value'])

Evaluate the Model

Summary of the model

In [8]:
pred_1 = model1.predict(housing[['median_income']])
mse_1 = mean_squared_error(housing['median_house_value'], pred_1)
mae_1 = mean_absolute_error(housing['median_house_value'], pred_1)
intercept_1 = model1.intercept_
slope_1 = model1.coef_

pred_2 = model2.predict(housing[['population']])
mse_2 = mean_squared_error(housing['median_house_value'], pred_2)
mae_2 = mean_absolute_error(housing['median_house_value'], pred_2)
intercept_2 = model2.intercept_
slope_2 = model2.coef_

pred_3 = model3.predict(housing[['households']])
mse_3 = mean_squared_error(housing['median_house_value'], pred_3)
mae_3 = mean_absolute_error(housing['median_house_value'], pred_3)
intercept_3 = model3.intercept_
slope_3 = model3.coef_
In [9]:
table = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': ['Median House Value vs. Median Income', 'Population vs. Median House Value', 'Number of Households vs. Median House Value'],
    'Intercept': [intercept_1, intercept_2, intercept_3],
    'Slope': [model1.coef_, model2.coef_, model3.coef_],
    'Mean Squared Error (MSE)': [mse_1, mse_2, mse_3],
    'Mean Absolute Error (MAE)': [mae_1, mae_2, mae_3]
})

print(table)

Conclusion¶

The insight obtained from the comparison and evaluation of the three models is that, among the variables considered (median income, population, and number of households), median income emerges as the most reliable predictor of median house value. This conclusion is drawn from the lower Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Mean Absolute Error (MAE) values observed in Model 1, indicating a better fit to the data compared to the models based on population and number of households. The positive slope in Model 1 suggests that as median income increases, median house value tends to increase, reinforcing the predictive strength of this variable. This insight underscores the importance of considering the impact of different predictor variables when building regression models and highlights the superior predictive power of median income in this particular analysis.
